{"cursor":"8728","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Chinese-language singer and actor\n| name = Fruit Chan image = Fruit Chan Tokyo Intl Filmfest 2009.jpg caption =\n| Fruit Chan at the Tokyo International Film Festival, 21 October 2009\n| birth_date = ancestry = Guangdong, China origin = Hong Kong birth_place =\n| Guangdong, China goldenbauhiniaawards = 'Best Director' 1997 [[Made in Hong\n| Kong (film)|Made in Hong Kong]]  'Best Screenplay' 2000 [[Durian\n| Durian]] goldenhorseawards = 'Best Director' 1997 [[Made in Hong Kong\n| (film)|Made in Hong Kong]] 2001 [[Hollywood Hong Kong]]  'Best Original\n| Screenplay' 1997 ''[[Made in Hong Kong (film)|Made in Hong\nKong]] 1999Little Cheung 2000Durian Durian''\n| hongkongfilmwards = 'Best Director' 1997 ''[[Made in Hong Kong\n| (film)|Made in Hong\nKong]] 'Best Screenplay' 2000Durian Durian''\n| hkfcsawards = 'Best Director' 1997 ''[[Made in Hong Kong\n| (film)|Made in Hong\nKong]] 'Best Screenplay' 2001Hollywood Hong Kong'' }}\n\n'Fruit Chan Gor' (; born April 15, 1959 in Guangdong, China) is an independent\nHong Kong Second Wave screenwriter, filmmaker and producer, who is best known\nfor his style of film reflecting the everyday life of Hong Kong people. He is\nwell known for using amateur actors (such as Sam Lee in [[Made in Hong Kong\n(film)|Made in Hong Kong]], Wong Yau-Nam in [[Hollywood Hong Kong]]) in his\nfilms. His name became familiar to many Hong Kongers only after the success of\nthe 1997 film Made in Hong Kong, which earned many local and international\nawards. Chan was deeply influenced by the era of sixties film in Japan, for the\nreason that they were not afraid to produce realistic movies that addressed\nsocietyâs problems. In particular, Nagisa Oshima, a Japanese director during the\nsixties was someone who Chan looked up to and thought of when directing Made in\nHong Kong.\n\nOn August 22, 2007, Chan announced that he will make a film focusing on Bruce\nLee's early years, specifically, the Chinese-language film, Kowloon City, will\nbe produced by John Woo's producer Terence Chang. The film will be set in 1950s\nHong Kong.\n\nChan's credits include [[Durian Durian]]. Also, Stanley Kwan stated that he was\ntalking with Lee's family to make a movie about the late action movie icon.\nFurther, in April, Chinese state media announced that its national broadcaster\nstarted filming a 40-part TV series on Bruce Lee to promote Chinese culture for\nthe 2008 Beijing Summer Olympics. [http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/08/22/arts/AS-A-E-MOV-Hong-\nKong-Bruce-Lee-Movie.php IHT, Report: Hong Kong director plans Bruce Lee\nbiopic]\n","linknr":293,"url":"Fruit_Chan","recorded":1375072350,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Fruit_Chan&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Fruit_Chan&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Fruit_Chan_Tokyo_Intl_Filmfest_2009.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Fruit_Chan_Tokyo_Intl_Filmfest_2009.jpg/220px-Fruit_Chan_Tokyo_Intl_Filmfest_2009.jpg","/wiki/Ancestral_home_(Chinese)","/wiki/Guangdong","/wiki/China","/wiki/Hong_Kong","/wiki/Guangdong","/wiki/China","/wiki/Hong_Kong_Film_Awards","/wiki/Made_in_Hong_Kong_(film)","/wiki/Dur